1. Problem Statement

Reddam House operated using Google Workspace (paid environment) for email and collaboration, while internal IT systems required Active Directory (on-prem) for device management, security policies, and access control.

This created:

1. Split identity systems (Google vs AD)
No single source of truth for ~200 users
Manual onboarding across platforms
Inconsistent access control policies

2. Environment
Google Workspace (Paid subscription)
Windows Server Active Directory (On-Prem)
Windows 10 endpoints
Mixed cloud + local infrastructure
Staff + student accounts

3. Architecture Overview
Google Workspace = Email, Docs, Collaboration
Active Directory = Device control, authentication, policies
No native integration initially

Goal:

Align Google identities with AD-managed devices and security policies

4. Implementation Process
Step 1: Audit Existing Google Workspace Users
Export all users from Google Admin Console
Identify duplicates, inactive accounts, and role groups
Step 2: Active Directory Structure Design
Created OU structure:
Staff
Students
Admin
IT Devices
Step 3: Identity Mapping
Matched Google Workspace users → AD users
Standardized naming conventions:
firstname.lastname format
Step 4: Device Integration
Joined Windows devices to Active Directory domain
Applied Group Policies:
Password rules
Desktop restrictions
Drive mappings
Step 5: Hybrid Workflow Setup
Google Workspace remained primary for email
AD used for:
Login authentication (PC access)
Security enforcement
Device control
Step 6: Migration Cleanup
Removed unused Google accounts
Disabled inactive AD accounts
Resolved permission conflicts

5. Pros
✔ No disruption to Google Workspace email system
✔ Centralized device control via Active Directory
✔ Improved security enforcement on endpoints
✔ Easier IT support for desktop environments
✔ Maintained cloud collaboration tools

6. Cons
❌ Two identity systems still exist (Google + AD)
❌ Syncing users manually introduces human error risk
❌ Increased administrative overhead
❌ No full Single Sign-On (SSO) without additional tools

7. Cost Considerations
Google Workspace (Paid)
Per-user licensing cost
Monthly subscription per account
Scales with staff/student count
Active Directory (On-Prem)
Windows Server licensing
Hardware/server maintenance
IT support overhead
Overall Cost Insight:

Dual-system environments increase operational cost but improve flexibility in education environments.
